  <header class="hero">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="label">Machine Learning Research Project</p>
      <h1>Alzheimer Disease Detection from Speech Audio</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">
        Comparing CNN, RNN, SVM, and Logistic Regression on spectrogram
        representations of speech to classify Alzheimer disease.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-meta">
        <span>Ibe Mohammed Ali</span>
        <span class="dot">&#183;</span>
        <span>Kubra Sag</span>
        <span class="dot">&#183;</span>
        <span>Poorav Rawat</span>
      </div>
      <div class="hero-links">
        <a href="https://github.com/ibeeeees/alzheimer-research" class="btn" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub Repository</a>
        <a href="#results" class="btn btn-ghost">View Results</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </header>

  <main>

    <section id="problem" class="container">
      <p class="section-label">Background</p>
      <h2>Why speech?</h2>
      <p>
        Clinical diagnosis of Alzheimer disease relies on costly cognitive
        assessments, neuroimaging, and biomarker analysis. Cognitive decline
        produces measurable changes in how people speak: longer pauses,
        reduced vocabulary, altered prosody, and less coherent descriptions.
      </p>
      <p>
        Speech is non-invasive, low-cost, and easy to collect. If a model can
        reliably detect Alzheimer from a short audio clip, it could enable
        earlier screening in primary care settings.
      </p>
      <div class="card-row">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>The Task</h3>
          <p>Given a recording of a person describing the Cookie Theft picture, predict: healthy or Alzheimer.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>The Dataset</h3>
          <p>131 real audio recordings from Kaggle: 76 healthy controls, 55 Alzheimer patients.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>The Question</h3>
          <p>Which model architecture best captures acoustic differences on a small clinical dataset?</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="method" class="container">
      <p class="section-label">Methodology</p>
      <h2>How we processed the audio</h2>
      <p>Raw .wav files go through a four-stage preprocessing pipeline before being fed to any model.</p>
      <div class="pipeline">
        <div class="pipeline-step">
          <span class="step-num">1</span>
          <div><h4>Resample</h4><p>All audio resampled to 16 kHz mono</p></div>
        </div>
        <div class="pipeline-arrow">&#8594;</div>
        <div class="pipeline-step">
          <span class="step-num">2</span>
          <div><h4>Normalize</h4><p>Peak amplitude normalized to [-1, 1]</p></div>
        </div>
        <div class="pipeline-arrow">&#8594;</div>
        <div class="pipeline-step">
          <span class="step-num">3</span>
          <div><h4>Pad / Truncate</h4><p>Fixed to 10 seconds (160,000 samples)</p></div>
        </div>
        <div class="pipeline-arrow">&#8594;</div>
        <div class="pipeline-step">
          <span class="step-num">4</span>
          <div><h4>Spectrogram</h4><p>Log-Mel spectrogram: 128 x 313</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="detail-box">
        <h4>What is a log-Mel spectrogram?</h4>
        <p>
          A spectrogram is a 2D image where the x-axis is time, the y-axis is frequency,
          and pixel intensity represents energy. The Mel scale compresses frequencies to
          match human perception. The log scales energy in decibels. The result: a 128 × 313
          matrix that captures what frequencies are present and when.
        </p>
        <p style="margin-top:0.75rem">The computation pipeline for each frame $\tau$:</p>
        <div class="math-display" is:raw>$$S(\tau, \omega) = \left|\sum_{n=0}^{N-1} x(n + \tau H) \cdot w(n) \cdot e^{-j2\pi\omega n / N}\right|^2$$</div>
        <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--text-muted)">Short-time Fourier transform (STFT) with window size $N=1024$, hop length $H=512$.</p>
        <div class="math-display" is:raw>$$\text{LogMel}(\tau, k) = \log\!\left(\sum_{\omega} S(\tau, \omega) \cdot m_k(\omega) + \varepsilon\right)$$</div>
        <p is:raw style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--text-muted)">$m_k(\omega)$ is the $k$-th triangular Mel filter bank weight ($k = 1 \ldots 128$), $\varepsilon = 10^{-9}$ prevents $\log 0$. Each audio file produces a $128 \times 313$ matrix at 16 kHz.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="detail-box">
        <h4>Configuration (config.py)</h4>
        <pre><code>SAMPLE_RATE    = 16000
N_MELS         = 128
N_FFT          = 1024
HOP_LENGTH     = 512
FEATURE_TYPE   = "logmel"
TRAIN / VAL / TEST = 70% / 15% / 15%</code></pre>
      </div>

      <h3 class="sub-title">Feature representations we tested</h3>
      <p style="font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-muted);margin-bottom:1.25rem">All three features are extracted from the same raw waveform using <code>librosa</code>. They differ in how much spectral detail they preserve and how they scale energy values.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- Feature grid — full viewport width, no container constraint -->
    <div class="feature-section-full">
      <div class="feature-grid">
        <div class="feature-card">
          <div class="feature-badge mfcc">MFCC</div>
          <h4>Mel-Frequency Cepstral Coefficients</h4>
          <img src={`${base}feat_mfcc.png`} alt="MFCC feature visualisation" class="feature-img" />
          <p>Compresses the log-Mel spectrum through a Discrete Cosine Transform (DCT), keeping only the first <code>n_mfcc=40</code> coefficients. Captures the overall <em>shape</em> of the spectrum — good for phoneme identity but discards fine-grained frequency detail needed for AD biomarkers.</p>
          <div class="feature-stat-row">
            <span class="fstat"><strong>Shape:</strong> 40 × 313</span>
            <span class="fstat"><strong>Size:</strong> 12,520 values</span>
            <span class="fstat fstat-bad">Loses spectral detail</span>
          </div>
          <div class="code-snippet" style="margin-top:0.6rem">
            <p class="code-label">data/features.py</p>
            <pre>features = librosa.feature.mfcc(
    y=audio, sr=sample_rate,
    <span class="hl-val">n_mfcc=40</span>,      <span class="hl-key"># 40 DCT coefficients kept</span>
    n_fft=1024, hop_length=512
)</pre>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="feature-card">
          <div class="feature-badge mel">Mel Spec</div>
          <h4>Mel Spectrogram</h4>
          <img src={`${base}feat_mel.png`} alt="Mel spectrogram visualisation" class="feature-img" />
          <p>Applies <code>n_mels=128</code> triangular filter banks spaced on the Mel scale to the STFT power spectrum. Preserves full frequency resolution but energy values span many orders of magnitude — makes learning harder as very loud and very quiet events dominate.</p>
          <div class="feature-stat-row">
            <span class="fstat"><strong>Shape:</strong> 128 × 313</span>
            <span class="fstat"><strong>Size:</strong> 40,064 values</span>
            <span class="fstat fstat-mid">Linear energy scale</span>
          </div>
          <div class="code-snippet" style="margin-top:0.6rem">
            <p class="code-label">data/features.py</p>
            <pre>features = librosa.feature.melspectrogram(
    y=audio, sr=sample_rate,
    <span class="hl-val">n_mels=128</span>,     <span class="hl-key"># 128 Mel filter banks</span>
    n_fft=1024, hop_length=512
)</pre>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="feature-card feature-card--best">
          <div class="feature-badge logmel">Log-Mel ✓ Best</div>
          <h4>Log-Mel Spectrogram</h4>
          <img src={`${base}feat_logmel.png`} alt="Log-Mel spectrogram visualisation" class="feature-img" />
          <p>Same as Mel spectrogram but energy converted to decibels via <code>power_to_db</code>. The log scale compresses the huge dynamic range so quiet events — hesitations, pauses, disfluencies characteristic of AD — become as visible as loud speech. Best results across all models.</p>
          <div class="feature-stat-row">
            <span class="fstat"><strong>Shape:</strong> 128 × 313</span>
            <span class="fstat"><strong>Size:</strong> 40,064 values</span>
            <span class="fstat fstat-good">Best for all models</span>
          </div>
          <div class="code-snippet" style="margin-top:0.6rem">
            <p class="code-label">data/features.py</p>
            <pre>mel = librosa.feature.melspectrogram(
    y=audio, sr=sample_rate,
    n_mels=128, n_fft=1024, hop_length=512
)
features = librosa.power_to_db(
    mel, <span class="hl-val">ref=np.max</span>  <span class="hl-key"># log scale, ref peak energy</span>
)</pre>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <section id="models" class="container container--wide">
      <p class="section-label">Model Architectures</p>
      <h2>Four approaches, one dataset</h2>
      <p>
        We deliberately selected models across the complexity spectrum — from a linear baseline to deep
        convolutional networks — to isolate whether additional model complexity actually helps given a
        small dataset. We excluded trivial baselines (k-NN, Naive Bayes, plain Decision Trees) in favor
        of models with meaningful inductive biases for structured audio data.
      </p>

      <div class="model-grid">
        <div class="model-card">
          <div class="model-tag deep">Deep Learning</div>
          <h3>CNN</h3>
          <p class="model-detail">Convolutional Neural Network</p>
          <p><strong>Why chosen:</strong> A log-Mel spectrogram is structurally identical to a grayscale image. CNNs learn translation-invariant local feature detectors, making them ideal for capturing localized frequency-time patterns in speech regardless of where in the 10-second window they occur.</p>
          <div class="math-box">
            <p class="math-label">Conv layer output:</p>
            <div class="math-display" is:raw>$$y_{i,j} = \sigma\!\left(\sum_{p,q} W_{p,q} \cdot x_{i+p,\, j+q} + b\right)$$</div>
            <p class="math-label">MaxPool (2×2):</p>
            <div class="math-display" is:raw>$$p_{i,j} = \max_{0 \le \delta_r, \delta_c < 2} y_{2i+\delta_r,\, 2j+\delta_c}$$</div>
            <p class="math-label">BatchNorm:</p>
            <div class="math-display" is:raw>$$\hat{x}_i = \frac{x_i - \mu_\mathcal{B}}{\sqrt{\sigma_\mathcal{B}^2 + \varepsilon}}$$</div>
            <p class="math-note">Three layers compress 128×313 → 64×156 → 32×78 → 16×39 via MaxPool. BatchNorm + Dropout(0.4) applied after each layer.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="model-specs">
            <span>10.3M params</span>
            <span>Filters: 32→64→128</span>
            <span>Dropout 0.4</span>
            <span>Adam lr=1e-3</span>
          </div>
          <p class="model-who">Implemented by <strong>Ibe</strong></p>
        </div>

        <div class="model-card">
          <div class="model-tag deep">Deep Learning</div>
          <h3>RNN (GRU)</h3>
          <p class="model-detail">Bidirectional Gated Recurrent Unit</p>
          <p><strong>Why chosen:</strong> Speech is fundamentally temporal. Alzheimer's-related pauses and disfluencies span the full utterance. A bidirectional GRU processes the spectrogram column-by-column (each column = one 32ms time frame), capturing long-range dependencies in both forward and reverse directions.</p>
          <div class="math-box">
            <p class="math-label">GRU update equations:</p>
            <div class="math-display" is:raw>$$z_t = \sigma(W_z x_t + U_z h_{t-1})$$</div>
            <div class="math-display" is:raw>$$r_t = \sigma(W_r x_t + U_r h_{t-1})$$</div>
            <div class="math-display" is:raw>$$\tilde{h}_t = \tanh\!\left(W x_t + U(r_t \odot h_{t-1})\right)$$</div>
            <div class="math-display" is:raw>$$h_t = (1 - z_t) \odot h_{t-1} + z_t \odot \tilde{h}_t$$</div>
          </div>
          <div class="model-specs">
            <span>511K params</span>
            <span>2-layer bidir GRU</span>
            <span>Hidden 128</span>
            <span>Dropout 0.3</span>
          </div>
          <p class="model-who">Implemented by <strong>Ibe</strong> &amp; <strong>Poorav</strong></p>
        </div>

        <div class="model-card">
          <div class="model-tag classical">Classical ML</div>
          <h3>SVM</h3>
          <p class="model-detail">Support Vector Machine (RBF kernel)</p>
          <p><strong>Why chosen:</strong> SVMs are well-known to perform strongly on <em>small, high-dimensional datasets</em> — exactly our regime (131 samples, 40,064-D features). The RBF kernel implicitly maps inputs to an infinite-dimensional feature space without computing it explicitly, and the convex optimization objective guarantees a unique global optimum.</p>
          <div class="math-box">
            <p class="math-label">SVM dual objective &amp; RBF kernel:</p>
            <div class="math-display" is:raw>$$\max_\alpha \sum_i \alpha_i - \frac{1}{2}\sum_{i,j}\alpha_i\alpha_j y_i y_j K(x_i, x_j)$$</div>
            <div class="math-display" is:raw>$$K(x_i, x_j) = \exp\!\left(-\gamma \|x_i - x_j\|^2\right)$$</div>
            <p class="math-label">Decision function:</p>
            <div class="math-display" is:raw>$$f(x) = \text{sign}\!\left(\sum_i \alpha_i y_i K(x_i, x) + b\right)$$</div>
            <p class="math-note" is:raw>Subject to $0 \le \alpha_i \le C$ and $\sum_i \alpha_i y_i = 0$. Only support vectors ($\alpha_i > 0$) define the boundary.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="model-specs">
            <span>RBF kernel</span>
            <span>C = 1.0</span>
            <span>γ = scale</span>
            <span>Flattened input</span>
          </div>
          <p class="model-who">Implemented by <strong>Kubra</strong></p>
        </div>

        <div class="model-card">
          <div class="model-tag classical">Classical ML</div>
          <h3>Logistic Regression</h3>
          <p class="model-detail">Regularized Linear Classifier (baseline)</p>
          <p><strong>Why chosen:</strong> Logistic Regression provides a linear performance floor — any model that can't beat it is not learning useful non-linear structure. It also provides interpretable feature weights, showing which spectrogram frequency bands are most diagnostic of Alzheimer's.</p>
          <div class="math-box">
            <p class="math-label">Binary cross-entropy loss with L2 regularization:</p>
            <div class="math-display" is:raw>$$\mathcal{L}(w) = -\sum_i\!\Big[y_i \log \sigma(w^\top x_i) + (1-y_i)\log(1-\sigma(w^\top x_i))\Big] + \lambda\|w\|^2$$</div>
            <p class="math-note" is:raw>where $\sigma(z) = \frac{1}{1+e^{-z}}$ is the sigmoid function and $\lambda = 1/C$.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="model-specs">
            <span>Linear classifier</span>
            <span>C = 1.0 (1/λ)</span>
            <span>Max 1000 iter</span>
            <span>MFCC features</span>
          </div>
          <p class="model-who">Implemented by <strong>Poorav</strong></p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- HYPERPARAMETER TUNING -->
    <section id="experiments" class="container">
      <p class="section-label">Experimental Design</p>
      <h2>Hyperparameter tuning</h2>
      <p>
        We systematically varied key hyperparameters using a grid search to select the best configuration
        for each model. All experiments used the same stratified 70/15/15 split with validation accuracy
        as the selection criterion.
      </p>

      <h3 class="sub-title">CNN — Architecture Search</h3>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Value 1</th><th>Value 2</th><th>Value 3</th><th>Best</th><th>Observation</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Dropout rate</td>
              <td><code>0.2</code></td><td><code>0.4</code></td><td><code>0.5</code></td>
              <td><strong>0.4</strong></td>
              <td>0.5 collapsed accuracy below chance; 0.2 overfit</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Learning rate</td>
              <td><code>1e-2</code></td><td><code>1e-3</code></td><td><code>1e-4</code></td>
              <td><strong>1e-3</strong></td>
              <td>1e-2 caused loss divergence; 1e-4 too slow to converge in 15 epochs</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Conv filter counts</td>
              <td><code>16/32/64</code></td><td><code>32/64/128</code></td><td><code>64/128/256</code></td>
              <td><strong>32/64/128</strong></td>
              <td>Larger filters worsened overfitting; smaller filters underfit</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="code-snippet">
        <p class="code-label">Best CNN config (models/cnn.py)</p>
        <pre>class CNN(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, <span class="hl-val">dropout=0.4</span>):        <span class="hl-key"># ← tuned: 0.2/0.4/0.5</span>
        super().__init__()
        self.block1 = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Conv2d(1, <span class="hl-val">32</span>, kernel_size=3, padding=1),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(<span class="hl-val">32</span>), nn.ReLU(),
            nn.MaxPool2d(2), nn.Dropout2d(dropout)
        )
        self.block2 = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Conv2d(<span class="hl-val">32</span>, <span class="hl-val">64</span>, kernel_size=3, padding=1),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(<span class="hl-val">64</span>), nn.ReLU(),    <span class="hl-key"># ← tuned: 16/32/64, 32/64/128, 64/128/256</span>
            nn.MaxPool2d(2), nn.Dropout2d(dropout)
        )
        self.block3 = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Conv2d(<span class="hl-val">64</span>, <span class="hl-val">128</span>, kernel_size=3, padding=1),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(<span class="hl-val">128</span>), nn.ReLU(),
            nn.MaxPool2d(2), nn.Dropout2d(dropout)
        )
        self.classifier = nn.Linear(128 * 16 * 39, 2)

optimizer = Adam(model.parameters(), <span class="hl-val">lr=1e-3</span>)  <span class="hl-key"># ← tuned: 1e-2/1e-3/1e-4</span></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="grid-heatmap-wrap">
        <p class="grid-caption">Validation accuracy across dropout × learning rate combinations — green box marks chosen config.</p>
        <img src={`${base}grid_cnn.png`} alt="CNN hyperparameter grid search heatmap" class="grid-heatmap-img" />
      </div>

      <h3 class="sub-title">RNN — Architecture Search</h3>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Value 1</th><th>Value 2</th><th>Value 3</th><th>Best</th><th>Observation</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Hidden size</td>
              <td><code>64</code></td><td><code>128</code></td><td><code>256</code></td>
              <td><strong>128</strong></td>
              <td>256 overfit on 91 training samples; 64 lacked capacity</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Num layers</td>
              <td><code>1</code></td><td><code>2</code></td><td><code>3</code></td>
              <td><strong>2</strong></td>
              <td>3 layers overfit severely; 1 layer missed temporal structure</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Dropout</td>
              <td><code>0.1</code></td><td><code>0.3</code></td><td><code>0.5</code></td>
              <td><strong>0.3</strong></td>
              <td>Minimal recall improvement across all values due to class imbalance</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="code-snippet">
        <p class="code-label">Best RNN config (models/rnn.py)</p>
        <pre>class RNN(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, input_size=128,
                 <span class="hl-val">hidden=128</span>,          <span class="hl-key"># ← tuned: 64/128/256</span>
                 <span class="hl-val">num_layers=2</span>,        <span class="hl-key"># ← tuned: 1/2/3</span>
                 <span class="hl-val">dropout=0.3</span>):        <span class="hl-key"># ← tuned: 0.1/0.3/0.5</span>
        super().__init__()
        self.gru = nn.GRU(
            input_size, hidden,
            num_layers=num_layers,
            batch_first=True,
            bidirectional=True,
            dropout=dropout
        )
        self.classifier = nn.Linear(hidden * 2, 2)

    def forward(self, x):
        out, _ = self.gru(x.permute(0, 2, 1))
        return self.classifier(out[:, -1, :])</pre>
      </div>
      <div class="grid-heatmap-wrap">
        <p class="grid-caption">Validation accuracy across hidden size × num layers combinations — green box marks chosen config.</p>
        <img src={`${base}grid_rnn.png`} alt="RNN hyperparameter grid search heatmap" class="grid-heatmap-img" />
      </div>

      <h3 class="sub-title">SVM — Hyperparameter Search</h3>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Value 1</th><th>Value 2</th><th>Value 3</th><th>Best</th><th>Observation</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Regularization C</td>
              <td><code>0.1</code></td><td><code>1.0</code></td><td><code>10.0</code></td>
              <td><strong>1.0</strong></td>
              <td>C=10 overfit training set; C=0.1 underfit decision boundary</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Kernel</td>
              <td><code>linear</code></td><td><code>rbf</code></td><td><code>poly</code></td>
              <td><strong>rbf</strong></td>
              <td>RBF outperformed linear by 5%; poly was numerically unstable</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Gamma (γ)</td>
              <td><code>scale</code></td><td><code>auto</code></td><td><code>0.001</code></td>
              <td><strong>scale</strong></td>
              <td is:raw>$\gamma = 1/(n_\text{features} \cdot \text{Var}(X))$ — most stable; 0.001 too smooth</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="code-snippet">
        <p class="code-label">Best SVM config (models/sklearn_models.py)</p>
        <pre>from sklearn.svm import SVC
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline

svm = Pipeline([
    ("scaler", StandardScaler()),
    ("svc", SVC(
        <span class="hl-val">kernel="rbf"</span>,       <span class="hl-key"># ← tuned: linear/rbf/poly</span>
        <span class="hl-val">C=1.0</span>,             <span class="hl-key"># ← tuned: 0.1/1.0/10.0</span>
        <span class="hl-val">gamma="scale"</span>,     <span class="hl-key"># ← tuned: scale/auto/0.001</span>
        probability=True
    ))
])
svm.fit(X_train.reshape(len(X_train), -1), y_train)</pre>
      </div>
      <div class="grid-heatmap-wrap">
        <p class="grid-caption">Validation accuracy across C × kernel combinations — green box marks chosen config.</p>
        <img src={`${base}grid_svm.png`} alt="SVM hyperparameter grid search heatmap" class="grid-heatmap-img" />
      </div>

      <h3 class="sub-title">Logistic Regression — Hyperparameter Search</h3>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Value 1</th><th>Value 2</th><th>Value 3</th><th>Best</th><th>Observation</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Regularization C</td>
