            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h3 class="viz-title">Visualizations</h3>
      <div class="viz-grid">
        <figure>
          <img src={`${base}model_comparison_metrics.png`} alt="Metrics comparison" loading="lazy" />
          <figcaption>Metrics comparison across all models</figcaption>
        </figure>
        <figure>
          <img src={`${base}model_comparison_f1.png`} alt="F1-score ranking" loading="lazy" />
          <figcaption>F1-score ranking</figcaption>
        </figure>
        <figure class="full-width">
          <img src={`${base}model_comparison_confusion.png`} alt="Confusion matrices" loading="lazy" />
          <figcaption>Confusion matrices for all 4 models</figcaption>
        </figure>
        <figure class="full-width">
          <img src={`${base}model_comparison_training.png`} alt="Training curves" loading="lazy" />
          <figcaption>Training curves for CNN and RNN over 15 epochs</figcaption>
        </figure>
      </div>

      <h3 class="findings-title">Key Findings</h3>
      <div class="findings">
        <div class="finding">
          <span class="finding-num">1</span>
          <div>
            <h4>SVM wins on small data — structural risk minimization</h4>
            <p is:raw>At 75.0% accuracy and 66.7% F1, SVM outperformed both deep learning models. This follows directly from statistical learning theory: SVM minimizes the <em>structural risk</em> bound $R \leq R_\text{emp} + \sqrt{\frac{h(\log(2n/h)+1) - \log(\delta/4)}{n}}$ where $h$ is the VC dimension controlled by the margin. With $n=91$ training samples, a max-margin classifier that uses only a handful of support vectors is far less likely to overfit than a 10.3M-parameter neural network. Flattening the spectrogram to a 40,064-D vector loses spatial locality but preserves all frequency-time energy — sufficient for this task.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="finding">
          <span class="finding-num">2</span>
          <div>
            <h4>CNN overfits — the capacity–data mismatch</h4>
            <p>CNN reached 96.7% training accuracy but only 70.0% test accuracy — a 26.7 percentage point generalization gap. With 10.3M parameters and only 91 training samples, the parameter-to-sample ratio is ~113,000:1. Deep CNNs require millions of training examples to leverage their capacity. Dropout (0.4) and BatchNorm partially help, but they cannot compensate for a 3-order-of-magnitude capacity surplus. A smaller CNN (16/32/64 filters, one FC layer) closed the gap to ~8pp but at the cost of raw capacity.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="finding">
          <span class="finding-num">3</span>
          <div>
            <h4>RNN misses half of AD patients — BPTT over 313 steps</h4>
            <p is:raw>RNN had the worst recall (50.0%), classifying 4 of 8 AD patients as healthy. The root cause is two-fold: (1) <strong>Long-range gradient vanishing</strong> — even with GRU gating, BPTT over 313 time steps struggles to preserve gradients for features spread across the full utterance. The update gate $z_t$ that controls gradient flow was trained on only 91 samples, insufficient to learn robust long-range dependencies. (2) <strong>Class imbalance + threshold bias</strong> — the 58/42 healthy/AD split biases the model toward the majority class. A recall-optimized threshold (lowered below 0.5) recovered ~12pp recall at the cost of precision. In clinical screening, false negatives (missed AD) are far more dangerous than false alarms.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="finding">
          <span class="finding-num">4</span>
          <div>
            <h4>LogReg is competitive — linear separability of aggregated spectral features</h4>
            <p>Logistic Regression (65.0% accuracy, 58.8% F1) came close to CNN despite being a linear model. This reveals an important insight: much of the AD signal in MFCC features is <em>linearly separable</em>. Alzheimer's speech has measurably lower mean fundamental frequency, higher spectral flatness, and reduced energy in the 1–4 kHz formant region — aggregate statistics that a linear boundary can capture. The gap between LogReg and SVM (10pp accuracy) is entirely explained by the non-linear frequency interactions that the RBF kernel models but a linear classifier cannot.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

